Yearly Time Series Plots¶

This code generates a bar chart depicting the total number of collisions each year. The DataFrame is grouped by year, and the count is calculated for each year. The results are plotted using matplotlib.pyplot, and additional details such as labels and annotations are included for clarity. The x-axis labels are formatted to display only the year in YYYY format for better readability.

In [30]:
## Total Number of Collisions Each Year

# Group by year and calculate the count
yearly_counts = temp_master_df.groupby('year').size()

# Plot the results
ax = yearly_counts.plot(kind='bar', title='Total Number of Collisions per Year', figsize=(12, 6))
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Total Number of Collisions (yearly)')

# Add labels at the top of each bar
for i, v in enumerate(yearly_counts):
    ax.text(i, v + 0.1, str(v), ha='center', va='bottom')

# Format x-axis labels to display only the year in YYYY format
plt.xticks(rotation=0, ha='center')

plt.show()

Monthly Time Series Plots¶

This code generates a bar chart depicting the total number of collisions each month. The 'month' column is extracted from the 'collision_datetime' column to facilitate grouping. Monthly counts are calculated using groupby and size. Month names are defined for better visualization. The x-axis labels are updated to display month abbreviations. The results are plotted using matplotlib.pyplot, and additional details such as labels and annotations are included for clarity.

In [27]:
## Total Number of Collisions Each Month

# Extract the month from the datetime column
temp_master_df['month'] = temp_master_df['collision_datetime'].dt.month

# Group by month and calculate the count
monthly_counts = temp_master_df.groupby('month').size()

# Define month names
month_names = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']

# Update the x-axis labels
monthly_counts.index = monthly_counts.index.map(lambda x: month_names[x-1])

# Plot the results
ax = monthly_counts.plot(kind='bar', title='Total Number of Collisions per Month', figsize=(12, 6))
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('Total Number of Collisions (monthly)')

# Add labels at the top of each bar
for i, v in enumerate(monthly_counts):
    ax.text(i, v + 0.1, str(v), ha='center', va='bottom')

plt.show()

This code generates a bar chart illustrating the average number of collisions each month. The 'year' and 'month' columns are extracted from the 'collision_datetime' column to enable grouping. The average count is calculated by grouping first by year and month and then taking the mean for each month. Similar to the previous example, month names are defined for better visualization, and x-axis labels are updated accordingly. The results are plotted using matplotlib.pyplot, and additional details such as labels and annotations are included for clarity.

In [28]:
## Average Number of Collisions Each Month

# Extract the year and month from the datetime column
temp_master_df['year'] = temp_master_df['collision_datetime'].dt.year

# Group by year and month, then calculate the average count
monthly_avg = temp_master_df.groupby(['year', 'month']).size().groupby('month').mean()

# Define month names
month_names = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']

# Update the x-axis labels
monthly_avg.index = monthly_avg.index.map(lambda x: month_names[x-1])

# Plot the results
ax = monthly_avg.plot(kind='bar', title='Average Number of Collisions per Month', figsize=(12, 6))
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('Average Number of Collisions (monthly)')

# Add labels at the top of each bar
for i, v in enumerate(monthly_avg):
    ax.text(i, v + 0.1, f'{v:.2f}', ha='center', va='bottom')

plt.show()

Seasonal Time Series Yearly Plot¶

This code segment extracts the season from the 'collision_datetime' column based on the month. Seasonal counts are calculated by grouping the DataFrame by year and season. The results are visualized using Seaborn, with a bar chart depicting the total number of collisions per year, grouped by season. Labels, titles, and annotations are added to enhance clarity and interpretation.

In [31]:
# Extract Season
temp_master_df['season'] = temp_master_df['collision_datetime'].dt.month.apply(lambda month: (
    'Summer' if month in [6, 7, 8] else
    'Spring' if month in [3, 4, 5] else
    'Winter' if month in [12, 1, 2] else
    'Fall'
))

# Count the number of rows for each Year and Season (unique combinations)
seasonal_counts_corrected = temp_master_df.groupby(['year', 'season']).size().reset_index(name='Collisions')

# Plotting using Seaborn with the modified color order
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
ax = sns.barplot(data=seasonal_counts_corrected, x='year', y='Collisions', hue='season', palette='Set1', ci=None)
plt.title('Total Number of Collisions per Year by Season')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Number of Collisions Grouped by Season')
plt.legend(title='Season', loc='upper right')

# Add labels at the top of each bar
for p in ax.patches:
    ax.annotate(f'{p.get_height():.0f}', (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), ha='center', va='bottom', xytext=(0, 5), textcoords='offset points', rotation=90)

plt.show()

Hourly Time Series Plot¶

This code segment extracts information related to week, month, and year, providing temporal dimensions for analysis. Two pivot tables are created to prepare data for heatmaps, one for monthly distribution and another for annual distribution. A new column 'HourOfDay' is added to represent the hour of the day based on the 'collision_datetime'. Hourly distribution of collisions is visualized using a bar plot with all bars in the same color, and annotations are added for clarity. Descriptive comments are updated to better reflect the purpose and functionality of each part of the code.

In [32]:
# Extract Week, Month, and Year
temp_master_df['week'] = temp_master_df['collision_datetime'].dt.isocalendar().week

# Create a pivot table for the heatmap by Monthly Distribution
heatmap_data_monthly = temp_master_df.pivot_table(index='INJURY', columns='month', values='collision_datetime', aggfunc='count')

# Create a pivot table for the heatmap by Annual Distribution
heatmap_data_annual = temp_master_df.pivot_table(index='INJURY', columns='year', values='collision_datetime', aggfunc='count')

# Create a new column for the hour of the day
temp_master_df['HourOfDay'] = temp_master_df['collision_datetime'].dt.hour

# Group by Hour of Day and calculate the count of occurrences
hourofday_counts = temp_master_df.groupby('HourOfDay').size().reset_index(name='Collisions')

# Plotting Hour of Day Bar Plot with all bars in the same color and annotations
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
ax = sns.barplot(data=hourofday_counts, x='HourOfDay', y='Collisions', color='b')
plt.title('Hourly Distribution of Collisions Throughout the Day')
plt.xlabel('Hour of Day')
plt.ylabel('Number of Collisions (hourly)')

# Add labels at the top of each bar
for p in ax.patches:
    ax.annotate(f'{p.get_height():.0f}', (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), ha='center', va='bottom')

plt.show()

This code calculates the average number of collisions for each hour of the day. The 'day' and 'hour' columns are extracted from the 'collision_datetime' column. The DataFrame is grouped by year, month, day, and hour, and the average count is calculated for each hour. Results are plotted using a bar chart to visualize the hourly distribution of average collision counts. Descriptive comments are updated to provide a clearer understanding of the code's purpose and functionality.

In [33]:
## Average Number of Collisions Each Hour

# Extract the day and hour from the datetime column
temp_master_df['day'] = temp_master_df['collision_datetime'].dt.day
temp_master_df['hour'] = temp_master_df['collision_datetime'].dt.hour

# Group by year, month, day, and hour, then calculate the average count
hourly_avg = temp_master_df.groupby(['year', 'month', 'day', 'hour']).size().groupby('hour').mean()

# Plot the results
ax = hourly_avg.plot(kind='bar', title='Average Number of Collisions per Hour', figsize=(12, 6))
plt.xlabel('Hour')
plt.ylabel('Average Number of Collisions (hourly)')

# Add labels at the top of each bar
for i, v in enumerate(hourly_avg):
    ax.text(i, v + 0.0, f'{v:.2f}', ha='center', va='bottom')

plt.show()

Weekend & Weekend Collisions Count¶

This code creates two new columns: 'DayOfWeek' to store the day of the week and 'IsWeekend' to indicate whether it's a weekend or weekday. The DataFrame is then grouped by 'IsWeekend', and the count of collisions for each group is calculated. The results are visualized using a bar plot comparing weekday and weekend collisions, with annotations for each count. Descriptive comments are updated to provide a clearer understanding of the code's purpose.

In [35]:
# Create a new column 'DayOfWeek' to store the day of the week
temp_master_df['DayOfWeek'] = temp_master_df['collision_datetime'].dt.day_name()

# Create a new column 'IsWeekend' to indicate whether it's a weekend or weekday
temp_master_df['IsWeekend'] = temp_master_df['collision_datetime'].dt.dayofweek // 5 == 1

# Group by 'IsWeekend' and calculate the count for each group
collision_counts = temp_master_df.groupby('IsWeekend').size()

# Plot the results with count annotations
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
ax = collision_counts.plot(kind='bar')
plt.title('Weekend vs. Weekday Collisions')
plt.xlabel('Day of the Week')
plt.ylabel('Number of Collisions')
plt.xticks([0, 1], ['Weekday', 'Weekend'], rotation=0)

# Add labels at the top of each bar
for p in ax.patches:
    ax.annotate(f'{p.get_height():.0f}', (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), ha='center', va='bottom')

plt.show()
